    "narrative": "Ghost Ride the WHIP enters today\u2019s slate with a high-ceiling lineup centered on **Mickey Moniak** (75.98) and **Jazz Chisholm Jr.** (74.79). **Mickey Moniak** is our most efficient play, capitalizing on a significant 14% park factor boost and a favorable matchup against Mike Burrows. Similarly, **Jazz Chisholm Jr.** remains a must-start; while the elite catcher behind the plate slightly dampens his score, the +11% SP skill advantage provided by Civale creates a massive ceiling for his stolen base potential. **Corbin Carroll** (67.08) rounds out our elite tier, earning extra points for his specific interaction with the opposing pitcher's slow delivery, which significantly inflates his theft opportunity against Peralta.\n\nOur most difficult roster decision involved leaving **Josh Naylor** (50.44) on the bench. Despite a solid base projection, he was squeezed out due to a difficult matchup against the high-skill arm of Eovaldi (3.17 xERA), which dropped his efficiency below the threshold established by **Zach McKinstry** and **Gabriel Moreno**. We are also monitoring the status of **Austin Riley** (60.39); while he slots in as a recommended start, his status remains \"Lineup Pending.\" Should he drop in the order or be held out, we are prepared to pivot to **Max Muncy**, though **Austin Riley**\u2019s base power profile currently keeps him ahead despite the looming risk. \n\nWe are avoiding the \"Below floor\" zone today by keeping **Kyle Karros** and **Alex Freeland** sidelined, as their bottom-third batting order positions severely cap their run-scoring upside. The path to a winning day relies on **James Wood** (71.11) capitalizing on his lead-off spot against Liberatore; if he can set the table, the combination of **Vinnie Pasquantino** (71.61) in the heart of the order and the speed threats of **Corbin Carroll** and **Jazz Chisholm Jr.** provides the best possible statistical hedge against our 5x5 scarcity issues.",
